  "local_port": 56030,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some good probiotic foods I should add to my diet?",
  "response": "Incorporating probiotic-rich foods into your diet can support gut health, improve digestion, and boost your immune system. Probiotics are live beneficial bacteria that help maintain a healthy balance in your digestive tract. Here are some excellent probiotic foods you might consider adding to your meals:\n\n1. **Yogurt**\n   - **Description:** One of the most well-known sources of probiotics.\n   - **Tips:** Look for labels that mention \"live and active cultures.\" Opt for plain yogurt to avoid added sugars and consider varieties like Greek yogurt for higher protein content.\n\n2. **Kefir**\n   - **Description:** A fermented milk drink similar to yogurt but with a thinner consistency.\n   - **Tips:** It contains a diverse range of probiotic strains. It can be consumed plain, flavored, or added to smoothies.\n\n3. **Sauerkraut**\n   - **Description:** Fermented cabbage that is rich in probiotics, particularly Lactobacillus.\n   - **Tips:** Choose unpasteurized sauerkraut, as pasteurization can kill beneficial bacteria. It's great as a condiment on sandwiches or as a side dish.\n\n4. **Kimchi**\n   - **Description:** A spicy Korean fermented vegetable dish, typically made with cabbage and radishes.\n   - **Tips:** Adds a flavorful kick to meals and provides a variety of probiotics and vitamins.\n\n5. **Miso**\n   - **Description:** A Japanese seasoning made from fermented soybeans, rice, or barley.\n   - **Tips:** Commonly used in miso soup, it can also be incorporated into marinades, dressings, and sauces. Add to foods after cooking to preserve the probiotics.\n\n6. **Tempeh**\n   - **Description:** A fermented soybean product with a firm texture and nutty flavor.\n   - **Tips:** A versatile meat substitute that can be grilled, stir-fried, or added to salads and sandwiches.\n\n7. **Kombucha**\n   - **Description:** A fermented tea beverage that contains a symbiotic culture of bacteria and yeast (SCOBY).\n   - **Tips:** Available in various flavors, it's a refreshing alternative to sugary drinks. Start with small amounts to see how your body reacts.\n\n8. **Pickles (Fermented)**\n   - **Description:** Cucumbers fermented in a brine without vinegar, which promotes the growth of probiotics.\n   - **Tips:** Check labels to ensure they are naturally fermented. They make a crunchy addition to snacks and meals.\n\n9. **Certain Cheeses**\n   - **Description:** Some aged cheeses like Gouda, cheddar, and Swiss contain probiotic cultures.\n   - **Tips:** Choose cheeses labeled with \"live and active cultures\" to ensure probiotic benefits.\n\n10. **Natto**\n    - **Description:** A traditional Japanese dish made from fermented soybeans.\n    - **Tips:** Known for its strong flavor and sticky texture, natto is rich in probiotics and vitamin K2. It can be eaten with rice or added to salads.\n\n11. **Fermented Vegetables**\n    - **Description:** Besides sauerkraut and kimchi, other fermented vegetables like carrots, beets, and green beans can provide probiotics.\n    - **Tips:** Incorporate a variety of fermented veggies into your diet for a range of flavors and nutrients.\n\n**Tips for Incorporating Probiotic Foods:**\n\n- **Start Slowly:** If you're new to fermented foods, introduce them gradually to allow your digestive system to adjust.\n- **Balance with Prebiotics:** Prebiotics are non-digestible fibers that feed probiotics. Foods like garlic, onions, bananas, and asparagus can help support probiotic bacteria.\n- **Read Labels Carefully:** Ensure that the products you choose contain live and active cultures and aren't pasteurized after fermentation, which can kill beneficial bacteria.\n- **Diversify Your Choices:** Consuming a variety of probiotic foods can provide different strains of beneficial bacteria, enhancing overall gut health.\n\n**Note:** While probiotic foods can be beneficial for many people, it's important to consult with a healthcare professional if you have any underlying health conditions or concerns, especially if you're considering significant dietary changes or have a compromised immune system.",
  "response_tokens": [
